  Decisions that change scope significantly

  The biggest scope-shifter is what does the user experience while unverified? Two paths:
  - Soft (recommended for Unwind): register → user is logged in immediately → small banner says "Verify your email to keep your 
  account safe" → app fully usable. Verification is informational. Easy to ship; lower friction for a relaxation tool.
  - Hard: register → no session → "Check your email" page → user clicks link → only then logged in. Adds a state machine on the 
  frontend, but more secure (prevents typo'd email addresses from squatting on accounts they can't recover).

  Soft saves you ~half a day. For a 100-user wellness app, soft is probably the right call.

  Hidden cost: sender domain (~half a day work + 1-2 days DNS waiting)

  To send from noreply@unwind.app (or your real domain), you need to:
  - Buy a domain (if you haven't yet — relevant for Stage 6 deployment too)
  - Add DKIM + SPF DNS records that Resend gives you
  - Wait for DNS propagation
  - Have Resend verify the domain

  You can defer this for development by using Resend's onboarding@resend.dev test sender, but production needs a real verified  
  domain. If you're deploying soon and don't have the domain yet, this is going to come up anyway — the email feature could     
  share that work.

  Total estimate

  Soft flow, Resend provider, real domain not yet acquired: 2-3 days of focused work, plus DNS waiting time. With AI-assisted   
  workflow and the review-based pacing in your CLAUDE.md (small chunks reviewed before moving on), figure 4-5 calendar days.    

  Soft flow, dev sender for now, defer domain: 1.5 days of focused work, ~3 calendar days. Buys you a working flow you can demo,
   deferring production-readiness.

  If you want to go further later: once email infrastructure exists, password reset is a 1-day add-on (same primitives — token, 
  email, verify endpoint, frontend route). Often worth doing both at the same time since you've already paid the integration    
  cost.

  What I'd suggest considering before committing

  - Worth writing an ADR for this — there are real decisions (provider, soft vs. hard, what counts as "verified" — the email    
  click only? plus a confirmation step?) that your future self will want documented. Fits the pattern in docs/adr/.
  - Stage 6 (deployment) is in flight. If you're getting a domain anyway for the prod deploy, line up the email DNS work to     
  happen at the same time so you only pay the DNS-waiting tax once.
  - This is a feature you can defer past launch. None of the current users are at risk without it. Once you have a real user    
  base, password recovery via email becomes more valuable, and that's the natural moment to add the whole email infrastructure. 

